  <detection>
    - Monitor Alt-Svc headers for QUIC enablement
    - Check for UDP port 443 traffic patterns
    - Analyze spin bit patterns for anomalies
    - Track connection migration events
    - Alert on 0-RTT requests to sensitive endpoints
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Confirm HTTP/3 support on target
    - Successfully replay 0-RTT requests
    - Demonstrate WAF bypass via QUIC
    - Identify amplification potential
    - Document security tool blind spots
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - Many CDNs enable HTTP/3 by default - always test both protocols
    - 0-RTT replay is most dangerous for financial transactions
    - Use tcpdump with QUIC dissector for packet analysis
    - Connection IDs in QUIC are like TCP sequence numbers - predict them
    - Chrome DevTools Protocol can force HTTP/3 for testing
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>HTTP/3 and QUIC represent a fundamental shift from TCP to UDP-based transport. Security tools are still catching up. The same vulnerability that's blocked over HTTP/1.1 may succeed over HTTP/3 simply because inspection tools don't understand QUIC. Always test both paths.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
